<paragraph id="F311E23DD55D2F011CDDFDCB4046FD18" blockId="15.[144,1104,533,749]" pageId="15" pageNumber="2144">
<taxonomicName id="34AE99BED55D2F011CDDFDCB438AFDD9" authority="Sakakibara &amp; Evangelista, 2010" authorityName="Sakakibara &amp; Evangelista" authorityYear="2010" box="[144,402,533,557]" class="Insecta" family="Membracidae" genus="Membracis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="2144" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="latifasciata" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis id="C1DA3E2FD55D2F011CDDFDCB438AFDD9" box="[144,402,533,557]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="2144">Membracis latifasciata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="DAE98354D55D2F011DD6FDCB43EFFDD8" box="[411,503,533,556]" pageId="15" pageNumber="2144" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
strongly resembles 
<taxonomicName id="34AE99BED55D2F011E90FDCB41A1FDD9" authority="Walker" authorityName="Walker" authorityYear="1858" box="[733,953,533,557]" class="Insecta" family="Membracidae" genus="Membracis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="2144" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="fusifera">
<emphasis id="C1DA3E2FD55D2F011E90FDCB4144FDD9" box="[733,860,533,557]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="2144">M. fusifera</emphasis>
Walker
</taxonomicName>
and also 
<taxonomicName id="34AE99BED55D2F011863FDCB43B9FDB9" authority="(DeGeer)" baseAuthorityName="DeGeer" baseAuthorityYear="1773" class="Insecta" family="Membracidae" genus="Membracis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="2144" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="foliataarcuata">
<emphasis id="C1DA3E2FD55D2F011863FDCB4334FDB9" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="2144">M. foliataarcuata</emphasis>
(DeGeer)
</taxonomicName>
regarding the shape of pronotum and the lateral yellowish bands. In the former, the yellow band is more or less fusiform and does not reach the anterior margin; in the latter species, on the other hand, the pronotum is more expanded, regularly rounded and the yellow band is much narrower, extending from the anterior margin to near the apex. In this new species, the yellow area of pronotum is far more extensive than the black area.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
